%N A396880 Decimal expansion of e * (3-e).
%C A396880 Real numbers are independently and uniformly selected at random from the interval (0, 1) until their sum exceeds 1. The expected number of selected numbers is e (see, e.g., Uspensky, 1937), and their expected variance is this constant (Russell, 1983).
%D A396880 J. V. Uspensky, Introduction to Mathematical Probability, New York: McGraw-Hill, 1937, pp. 277-278.
%H A396880 A. V. Boyd, <a href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/3619434">78.5 Bell Numbers and the Surprising Appearance of e</a>, The Mathematical Gazette, Vol. 78, No. 481 (1994), pp. 56-59.
%H A396880 Joel E. Cohen, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1080/00031305.2023.2244542">First-Passage Times for Random Partial Sums: Yadrenko's Model for e and Beyond</a>, The American Statistician, Vol. 78, No. 1 (2024), pp. 111-114; <a href="https://lab.rockefeller.edu/cohenje/assets/file/465FirstPassageTimes4RandomPartialSumsYadrenkosModel4eAmerStatistician2024.pdf">alternative link</a>.
%H A396880 K. G. Russell, <a href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/3213732">On the Number of Uniform Random Variables Which Must Be Added to Exceed a Given Level</a>, Journal of Applied Probability, Vol. 20, No. 1 (1983), pp. 172-177.
%H A396880 K. G. Russell, <a href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/2685243">Estimating the Value of e by Simulation</a>, The American Statistician, Vol. 45, No. 1 (1991), pp. 66-68.
%H A396880 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="http://mathworld.wolfram.com/UniformSumDistribution.html">Uniform Sum Distribution</a>.
%H A396880 <a href="/index/Tra#transcendental">Index entries for transcendental numbers</a>.
%F A396880 Equals A001113 * A153805.
%e A396880 0.765789386446485478850434953482979680091425710548031...
%t A396880 RealDigits[E * (3 - E), 10, 120][[1]]
%o A396880 (PARI) my(e = exp(1)); e * (3 - e)
